left class=m><span class=title> Re: Can true relationships be formed over the Internet?</span><hr size=1> Yes, but they don't always turn out as true as they might seem.  2 examples based from the same origin.<br>
<br>
My SO and I have been together going on 5 years now.  We met in a chat forum called Palace.  It started as a pay only forum which led to a much tighter knit community.  They have regular parties similar to EQ fanfaires, and of the 80 or so &quot;regulars&quot; in my circle of friends that have been around since Palace first went online, I would estimate I've met all of them in person at least once.  We live next door to a couple who also met on palace (one was an rl friend of ours and the other moved here from Canada), and they have been together about a year longer than we have if you count online and rl time.  There are dozens of other stories like this because the Palace userbase was much larger than just the circle of people we met on the server we frequented.<br>
<br>
Ok that's all the shiney-happy side of it.  Now the downside.  There was a woman who frequented our palace server who many people came to care about greatly.  She was HIV positive and just starting to show the first signs of full blown AIDS.  She was married to a man who was abusive, apparently because she became infected through an extra-marital affair.  About a year after she first started coming to palace, one of the server admin's received mail from her sister, explaining that she had killed herself.  <br>
<br>
The entire Palace community was shocked and saddened by this.  Palace is a grapical chat - you wear an image and sit in a &quot;room&quot; rather than watching lines of text on a screen, so as soon as the news spread a memorial room was created for her.  People filled it with images that had special meaning associated with her, or screencaps of happier conversations with her.  People around the world were honestly mourning this woman, and helping each other through very real grief.<br>
<br>
A month later it was discovered that it had all been a lie.  One of the admins phoned her &quot;sister&quot; because many palace users had asked if there was somewhere they could send donations for AIDS research, etc, in her name.  Her husband answered the phone and was quite shocked to hear all the details of his supposedly dying abused wife who happened to be in the next room making dinner.  This woman was never sick, never abused by her husband, and most importantly, never killed herself.  She was the sister that sent the email, and she was the sister who came to the palace server afterwards to accept the condolences of so many strangers.  In a sense, she faked her own death to cover up her lies and witness her own &quot;funeral&quot;.<br>
<br>
Here's the question for you - the relationships she made were obviously not real for her, but does it lessen the relationships that were felt by those who mourned her death, or the betrayal they felt when they learned the truth? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/umeddik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Meddik</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.aodoctors.org/Cross.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Safehouse Supporter</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/7/02 9:04:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseoutsidenorrath.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6045.topic&index=34>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Can true relationships be formed over the Internet?</span><hr size=1> Hmm...<br>
